    <p>Here's what happened to almost every man who's ever tried to track protein on a calorie app: Day 1, you log everything. Day 4, you're still doing it but it's getting annoying. Day 10, you realize you just spent 6 minutes logging a chicken sandwich. Day 14, you don't open the app at all.</p>

    <p>That's not a discipline problem. That's a design problem.</p>

    <p>The apps weren't built for you. They were built for competitive athletes, dietitians, and people who genuinely want to optimize 47 nutritional variables. Most men over 40 just want to know one thing: <strong>did I hit my protein today?</strong></p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      Not lack of effort.<br><span>Lack of visibility.</span>
    </div>

    <h2>Why Macro Tracking Feels Like a Part-Time Job After 40</h2>

    <p>The big calorie apps — MyFitnessPal, Cronometer, Lose It — were designed on the assumption that more data equals better results. And for some people, that's true. But for men over 40 who are simply trying to eat enough protein to protect muscle mass, the complexity actively works against you.</p>

    <p>Consider what happens every time you log a meal on a full macro tracker:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Search a food database with 14 versions of "grilled chicken breast"</li>
      <li>Estimate portion size in grams (do you own a food scale?)</li>
      <li>Watch calories, carbs, fat, sodium, and fiber numbers update in real time</li>
      <li>Repeat this 4–5 times per day</li>
      <li>Feel vaguely guilty about whatever the app flagged in red</li>
    </ul>

    <p>That's a lot of friction for a man who just wants to make sure he got enough protein to preserve muscle while he's fighting the natural decline that starts in his 40s.</p>

