    <h2>The 80/20 Truth About Your Diet After 40</h2>

    <p>Here's something that rarely gets said out loud: most men over 40 eat the same 8–12 foods on rotation every week. Eggs in the morning. Chicken or a burger at lunch. A protein shake somewhere. Maybe Greek yogurt. Steak on weekends.</p>

    <p>You don't need a database of 8 million foods. You need <em>your</em> 10 foods — with their protein numbers already in front of you.</p>

    <p>That's the entire premise behind keeping protein tracking simple. You don't need to discover new foods to hit your protein goal. You need to see <a href="/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120g actually looks like</a> in the foods you already eat — and then make sure you're hitting that number consistently.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The real problem isn't knowledge.</strong> Most men over 40 know they should eat more protein. The problem is that they can't see their number. By dinner time, they genuinely don't know if they've hit 60g or 110g. That gap — between intention and visibility — is where muscle is lost.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What "Easy" Actually Looks Like for Protein Tracking</h2>

    <p>Easy doesn't mean skipping tracking altogether. Skipping it means going back to guessing — and guessing is how most men end up eating 70g of protein on a day they thought was "pretty good."</p>

    <p>Easy means building a system that has almost no friction between you and your number. Here's what that looks like in practice:</p>

