    <p>The goal isn't precision to the gram. The goal is knowing — with enough accuracy to act on — whether you're on track. A man who consistently hits within 10g of his target beats a man who logs perfectly for 12 days and then quits cold.</p>

    <h2>The Protein Number That Matters Most After 40</h2>

    <p>Before you track anything, you need a target. For most active men over 40, that's in the range of 0.7–1g per pound of bodyweight. A 180-pound man is looking at roughly 125–180g per day.</p>

    <p>Starting at <strong>120g</strong> is a practical baseline — it's achievable without eating perfectly, it's enough to make a real difference in muscle preservation, and it's a clear enough target to measure against. Once 120g becomes automatic, you can push higher if your goals call for it.</p>

    <p>We've done a full breakdown of <a href="/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120g of protein actually looks like in real meals</a> — it's the most practical starting point if you haven't seen it yet.</p>

    <div class="author-note">
      <div class="an-label">A Note From Robert</div>
      <p>I spent years logging food in apps that told me more than I needed to know. I knew my fiber intake. I knew my sodium. I did not know, reliably, whether I was getting enough protein — because it was buried under all the other numbers. That's the irony of a tool that tracks everything: it can make the thing you actually care about harder to see. Building SnapProtein was my way of solving that for myself first. Turned out a lot of other men over 40 had the same problem.</p>
    </div>

